{{Nihongo|'''Seiken-ji'''|清見寺|}},  is a [[:en:Buddhist temples in Japan|Buddhist temple]] belonging to the [[Myōshin-ji]] branch of the [[Rinzai school]] of [[:en:Japanese Zen|Japanese Zen]], located in the Okitsu neighborhood of [[Shimizu-ku, Shizuoka|Shimizu-ku]] ward of the city of [[Shizuoka, Shizuoka]], [[:en:Japan|Japan]]. Its [[honzon|main image]] is a statue of [[:en:Gautama Buddha|Shaka Nyōrai]]. It is also called Kiyomi-dera.

==History==
The temple claims to have been founded in the [[:en:Hakuchi (era)|Hakuchi era]] of the [[:en:Nara period|Nara period]] as a [[Tendai]] sect temple to protect the {{nihongo|Kiyomi-seki|清見関|}}, a natural barrier on the ancient [[Tōkaidō (road)|Tōkaidō]] highway connecting the capital with eastern Japan, where the path of the road was a narrow ledge between cliffs and the [[Pacific Ocean]].  The temple subsequently fell into disrepair and was revived and converted to the Rinzai school by the monk [[:en:Enni|Enni]] in 1262 AD. The temple flourished during the [[:en:Muromachi period|Muromachi period]] and was named one of the [[Five Mountain System#The ''Jissetsu''|''Jissetsu'' temples]] in 1343. It is where [[:en:Ashikaga Takauji|Ashikaga Takauji]] and [[:en:Imagawa Yoshimoto|Imagawa Yoshimoto]] took the tonsure. In the [[Sengoku period]], when the young [[Tokugawa Ieyasu]] was held hostage in [[Sunpu Domain|Sunpu]] by the [[Imagawa clan]], he was sent to Seiken-ji to be tutored by the abbot [[Sessai Chōrō]]. During the invasion of [[Suruga Province]] by the [[Takeda clan]], [[:en:Imagawa Ujizane|Imagawa Ujizane]] established his headquarters at this temple.

