The temple claims to have been founded in the [[:en:Hakuchi (era)|Hakuchi era]] of the [[:en:Nara period|Nara period]] as a [[:en:Tendai|Tendai]] sect temple to protect the {{nihongo|Kiyomi-seki|清見関|}}, a natural barrier on the ancient [[Tōkaidō (road)|Tōkaidō]] highway connecting the capital with eastern Japan, where the path of the road was a narrow ledge between cliffs and the [[:en:Pacific Ocean|Pacific Ocean]].  The temple subsequently fell into disrepair and was revived and converted to the Rinzai school by the monk [[:en:Enni|Enni]] in 1262 AD. The temple flourished during the [[:en:Muromachi period|Muromachi period]] and was named one of the [[Five Mountain System#The ''Jissetsu''|''Jissetsu'' temples]] in 1343. It is where [[:en:Ashikaga Takauji|Ashikaga Takauji]] and [[:en:Imagawa Yoshimoto|Imagawa Yoshimoto]] took the tonsure. In the [[:en:Sengoku period|Sengoku period]], when the young [[Tokugawa Ieyasu]] was held hostage in [[:en:Sunpu Domain|Sunpu]] by the [[Imagawa clan]], he was sent to Seiken-ji to be tutored by the abbot [[:en:Sessai Chōrō|Sessai Chōrō]]. During the invasion of [[:en:Suruga Province|Suruga Province]] by the [[Takeda clan]], [[:en:Imagawa Ujizane|Imagawa Ujizane]] established his headquarters at this temple.

During the [[:en:Edo period|Edo period]], the temple continued to flourish due to its connection with Tokugawa Ieyasu, and its location on the Tōkaidō highway linking [[:en:Edo|Edo]] with [[:en:Kyoto|Kyoto]]. It was selected by the [[Tokugawa shogunate]] as one of the lodging spots for the [[:en:Joseon missions to Japan|Joseon missions to Japan]] and the delegations from the [[:en:Ryukyu Kingdom|Ryukyu Kingdom]].  Due to these connections it was designated a [[Monuments of Japan|National Historic Site of Japan]] in 1994.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://bunka.nii.ac.jp/heritages/detail/206953 |title=朝鮮通信使遺跡|language=Japanese |publisher=[[Agency for Cultural Affairs]] |accessdate=}}</ref> Surviving Edo period structures include the ''[[Sanmon]]'' (1651) and entrance to the [[:en:Main Hall (Japanese Buddhism)|Main Hall]] (1616).<ref name="Shiseki">{{cite book |last1=Isomura |first1=Yukio |last2=Sakai |first2=Hideya |title=(国指定史跡事典) National Historic Site Encyclopedia |date=2012 |publisher=学生社 |isbn=978-4311750403}}{{in lang|ja}}</ref>

During the early [[:en:Meiji era|Meiji era]], the tracks of the [[Tōkaidō Main Line]] railway were laid across the front of the temple, which lost much of its properties. However, due to its scenic location overlooking [[:en:Suruga Bay|Suruga Bay]], the temple drew the attention of poets and writers, including [[Shimazaki Tōson]], [[:en:Takayama Chogyū|Takayama Chogyū]] and [[:en:Natsume Sōseki|Natsume Sōseki]].<ref name="Shiseki"/>

The temple was also the location of an important conference held by the leadership of the fledgling [[:en:Imperial Japanese Navy|Imperial Japanese Navy]] in June 1887, with the participants discussing various tactics and [[:en:Naval strategy|fleet maneuvers]], which would then be tested in practice by the fleet in nearby Shimizu harbor.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Evans |first1=David C |last2=Peatty |first2=Mark |title=Kaigun: Strategy, Tactics, and Technology in the Imperial Japanese Navy, 1887-1941 |date=2012 |publisher=Naval Institute Press |isbn=978-1591142447 |pages=35–36}}</ref>

==Cultural properties==

===National Important Cultural Properties===
====Diary of Ye Mengde====
Diary of '''Ye Mengde''' ({{zh|t=葉夢得|w='''Yeh Meng-te'''}}; 1077–1148), a [[Song dynasty]] Chinese scholar, poet, and government minister, dated summer of 1149 AD<ref name="Bunka1">{{cite web |url= http://bunka.nii.ac.jp/heritages/detail/156808|title=宋版石林先生尚書伝 自巻第一至第四 紹興二十九年仲夏刊記|language=Japanese |publisher=[[Agency for Cultural Affairs]] |accessdate=}}</ref>

===National Place of Scenic Beauty===
==== Seiken-ji gardens====
The [[:en:Japanese garden|Japanese garden]] at Seiken-ji dates from the early Edo period and contains ponds and tree arrangements. It became a nationally designated [[Monuments of Japan|Place of Scenic Beauty]] in 1936.<ref name="Bunka2">{{cite web |url= http://bunka.nii.ac.jp/heritages/detail/162831|title=清見寺庭園|language=Japanese |publisher=[[Agency for Cultural Affairs]] |accessdate=}}</ref>

